    <h3>What is a VIN?</h3>
    <p>A VIN (Vehicle Identification Number) is a unique 17-character code assigned to every motor vehicle when it is manufactured. It serves as the vehicle's fingerprint, since no two vehicles in operation have the same VIN. The VIN standard was established in 1981 by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA).</p>

    <h3>Where can I find my VIN?</h3>
    <p>The most common locations are the lower-left corner of the dashboard (visible through the windshield), the driver's side door jamb, your vehicle registration card, and your insurance documents. Some vehicles also have the VIN stamped on the engine block or frame rail.</p>

